
Part 1 — Understanding Pinecone vs SQL
Before understanding Adele's architecture, it's important to understand why we use two databases:
	• Postgres (SQL)
	• Pinecone (Vector Database)
They solve different problems.

SQL: The Structured Knowledge System
Postgres is used to store structured information about Adele's knowledge.
Think of SQL as the library catalog.
It tells us:
	• What frameworks exist
	• Which repositories use which framework
	• Which documents belong to each framework
	• Where rules came from
	• When rules were created or updated
Example tables:

frameworks
repositories
documents
document_chunks
reviews
review_comments

SQL answers questions like:

Which framework does this repo belong to?

Which document contains this rule?

When was this rule added?

What document produced this chunk?
SQL is excellent for relationships and metadata.

Pinecone: The Semantic Search Engine
Pinecone is used to store vector embeddings of text.
Instead of storing structured data, Pinecone stores numerical representations of meaning.
This allows Adele to ask questions like:

"What rule is most relevant to this code?"
Example:
A developer writes code like:

CREATE TABLE sales_data
Adele may search Pinecone with a query like:

"MIW naming conventions for warehouse tables"
Pinecone returns the most semantically similar rule.
Example returned chunk:

"All warehouse tables must follow snake_case naming conventions."

Why We Don't Store Everything in Pinecone
Pinecone is not a relational database.
It is optimized for similarity search, not system structure.
If we stored everything only in Pinecone, we would lose the ability to easily answer questions like:

Which framework does this rule belong to?

Which document created this embedding?

When was this rule last updated?
This is why Adele stores metadata in SQL and embeddings in Pinecone.

Why We Store Chunks in SQL
When documents are processed, they are split into smaller pieces called chunks.
Example document:

MIW Data Modeling Standards
Example content:

1. All warehouse tables must include audit columns
2. Naming conventions must follow snake_case
3. Fact tables must contain surrogate keys
4. Dimension tables must support SCD Type 2
Instead of embedding the entire document, we split it.
Example chunks:
Chunk 1

All warehouse tables must include audit columns
Chunk 2

Naming conventions must follow snake_case
Chunk 3

Fact tables must contain surrogate keys
These chunks are:
Stored in SQL for traceability, and
Embedded into Pinecone for semantic search.

Why This Matters
Storing chunks in SQL allows us to:
1. Trace where rules came from
If Adele flags an issue, we can trace it back to the source document.

Chunk → Document → Framework

2. Rebuild embeddings later
If we upgrade embedding models in the future, we can easily regenerate embeddings using stored chunk text.

3. Filter rules by framework
Adele must apply different rules depending on whether a repository uses:
	• MEF
	• MIW
	• MIF
SQL allows us to filter documents and rules by framework before querying Pinecone.

Mental Model
A helpful way to understand the system:

Postgres = Library catalog
Pinecone = Librarian who finds relevant pages
The catalog tells us:
	• which book
	• which author
	• which category
The librarian helps find the most relevant paragraph.
Both are required.

Rule of thumb for this current architecture 
-Postgres stores structure (truth).	Pinecone stores meaning (vectors).


PT2 — Adele Database Architecture
Overview
Adele’s database architecture is responsible for storing:
	• framework standards
	• repository framework mappings
	• rule documents
	• code context
	• review results
	• ranking and feedback data
The system uses two data systems:
Postgres (SQL)
Stores structured data, relationships, and source records.
Pinecone (Vector Database)
Stores vector embeddings used for semantic retrieval.
The separation allows Adele to maintain structured traceability while enabling semantic search across large bodies of text and historical review data.

High Level Database Architecture

Adele Knowledge Layer

Postgres (Structured Data)
--------------------------------
frameworks
repositories
documents
document_chunks
code_context
review_jobs
reviews
review_comments
ranked_responses
human_feedback


Pinecone (Semantic Memory)
--------------------------------
framework rule embeddings
code context embeddings
ranked response embeddings
human feedback embeddings
Postgres stores the source of truth, while Pinecone stores vector representations of that information for semantic retrieval.

Postgres Database Structure
The Postgres database is divided into four main functional groups.

1. Framework Knowledge
2. Code Context
3. Review System
4. Ranking & Learning Data

1 Framework Knowledge Tables
These tables define the standards Adele uses when reviewing code.

frameworks
Defines the Minerva frameworks Adele understands.

frameworks
-----------
framework_id (PK)
name
description
created_at
Example records:
framework_id	name	description
1	MEF	Minerva Engineering Framework
2	MIW	Minerva Information Warehouse
3	MIF	Minerva Ingestion Framework
This table enables Adele to apply framework-specific review standards.

repositories
Maps repositories to their framework.

repositories
------------
repo_id (PK)
repo_name
framework_id (FK)
created_at
Example:
repo_name	framework
warehouse-service	MIW
ingestion-pipeline	MIF
This allows Adele to determine which standards apply to a repository.

documents
Stores the original files containing framework rules or standards.

documents
-----------
document_id (PK)
repo
file_path
framework_id (FK)
doc_type
created_at
Example doc_type values:

rule
guideline
example
policy
A document represents a full rule source, such as architecture documentation or coding standards.

document_chunks
Documents are split into smaller text segments for embedding.

document_chunks
----------------
chunk_id (PK)
document_id (FK)
chunk_text
chunk_index
embedding_id
created_at
Example chunk:

Naming conventions must follow snake_case.
Each chunk corresponds to one vector stored in Pinecone.
Chunking allows Adele to retrieve specific rule fragments instead of entire documents.

2 Code Context Tables
These tables store historical code context used during reviews.

code_context
Stores snippets of historical code data.

code_context
-------------
context_id (PK)
repo_id (FK)
file_path
commit_hash
code_snippet
created_at
Example stored data:

Previous version of ingestion pipeline before refactor
Embedding this information allows Adele to understand:
	• historical implementation patterns
	• previous architecture decisions
	• similar code structures

3 Review System Tables
These tables store Adele’s review operations and results.

review_jobs
Tracks background processing jobs.

review_jobs
-----------
job_id (PK)
repo_id (FK)
pr_number
status
created_at
started_at
completed_at
Possible statuses:

queued
processing
completed
failed

reviews
Stores metadata about completed reviews.

reviews
--------
review_id (PK)
repo_id (FK)
pr_number
framework_id (FK)
status
created_at
Example:
review_id	repo	pr_number	status
101	warehouse-service	54	completed

review_comments
Stores the suggestions generated by Adele.

review_comments
---------------
comment_id (PK)
review_id (FK)
file_path
line_number
severity
message
suggestion
created_at
Example:
severity	message
medium	Table name should follow snake_case

4 Ranking & Learning Tables
These tables support Adele’s ranking and improvement systems.

ranked_responses
Stores labeled responses used to train the ranking system.

ranked_responses
----------------
response_id (PK)
review_comment_id (FK)
response_text
label
created_at
Example labels:

good
bad
corrected
Embedding these responses allows Adele to compare new suggestions with historically successful ones.

human_feedback
Stores feedback provided by engineers.

human_feedback
---------------
feedback_id (PK)
review_comment_id (FK)
feedback_text
feedback_type
created_at
Example feedback types:

approval
correction
rejection
This data allows Adele to improve recommendations based on real developer input.

Pinecone Semantic Index
Pinecone stores vector embeddings derived from Postgres data.
These embeddings allow Adele to retrieve information based on semantic similarity rather than exact keywords.

Pinecone Data Types
The Pinecone index may contain multiple embedding categories.

framework_rule
code_context
ranked_response
human_feedback
Each vector includes metadata referencing the original SQL record.
Example metadata:

type: framework_rule
framework_id: 2
document_id: 42
chunk_id: 3

Relationship Between Postgres and Pinecone

frameworks
    │
    ▼
documents
    │
    ▼
document_chunks
    │
    │ embedding_id
    ▼
Pinecone vectors
Additional embeddings may originate from:

code_context
ranked_responses
human_feedback
All embeddings reference their source record in Postgres.

Key Architectural Principle
Adele separates structured knowledge from semantic retrieval.

Postgres
-----------
system structure
relationships
source data
review history

Pinecone
-----------
semantic embeddings
vector similarity search
context retrieval
This separation provides:
	• traceability
	• improved debugging
	• flexible retrieval
	• scalable embedding updates

